[1] _Dickeya solani_ - UK (Scotland)
Date: Thu 27 May 2010
Source: Business Scotsman [edited]
<http://business.scotsman.com/business/Alert-after-Dutch-potato-disease.6322483.jp>


Alert after Dutch potato disease found in Scotland
--------------------------------------------------
The discovery of a highly infectious crop disease in a field of
potatoes near Coupar Angus [Perthshire] has shocked Scottish seed
potato growers this week. _Dickeya solani_ causes the tubers and
haulm [stalks] to rot, and outbreaks in England have been linked to
purchases of seed potatoes from the Netherlands, which has suffered
several outbreaks.

Efforts have been made to keep it out of Scotland [see ProMED-mail
post 20100208.0421]. The Scottish potato industry set up a "safe
haven" programme intended to prevent seed [tubers] coming from areas
faced with infection. Now, it appears that seed of a new Dutch bred
variety called Innovator has been brought north from England and
planted in the centre of a major seed growing area in Perthshire.

The Scottish Government agency Science and Advice for Scottish
Agriculture [SASA] has already said the crop will be destroyed as
soon as possible and the seed put to landfill. However, _Dickeya
solani_ can live in the soil for a long time and can be spread
through water courses, with potentially serious implications for
other growers downstream. The infection is currently limited to one
field on one farm and was picked up as part of a Scottish Government
inspection.

[Byline: Andrew Arbuckle]

